<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-a-cube">
    <title>Surface area of a cube</title>
     <p>
        In this section, you will calculate the surface area of a cube from the nets.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <title></title>
        <statement>

            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>What you need:</term>  A piece of Paper,A pencil,A ruler and A pair scissors.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a net of a cube on a piece of paper, ensuring it has <m>6</m> connected squares. Each square represents a face of the cube as shown below.
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            <latex-image label="cube-net1">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Drawing the vertical part of the net with different colors
                                \fill[yellow!50] (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Missing line
                                \draw (0,4) -- (4,4);
                                
                                % Drawing the horizontal part of the net with different colors
                                \fill[green!50] (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);
                                
                                \fill[blue!50] (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                                \fill[orange!50] (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- cycle;
                                \fill[cyan!50] (-4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (-4,0) -- cycle;
                                \fill[purple!50] (4,-4) -- (8,-4) -- (8,0) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Drawing the edges
                                \draw (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                                \draw (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);
                                
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            
                        </image>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (a). Use your ruler to measure the side length of one square and record it down.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            (b).  Work out the area of each face of the net.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (c). Work out the total area of the faces
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss your results with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The surface area of a cube is the total area of all six faces of the cube. 
                    When learning about area, you calculated the surface area of a cube by adding up the areas of all six faces.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
                    <p>
                        The figure below show a cube.
                    </p>

                    <image width="50%"> 
                    <latex-image label="cbe-1">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                       
                       % Define cube vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,0,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (4,4,0);
                        \coordinate (D) at (0,4,0);
                        \coordinate (E) at (0,0,4);
                        \coordinate (F) at (4,0,4);
                        \coordinate (G) at (4,4,4);
                        \coordinate (H) at (0,4,4);

                        % Draw cube faces with colors
                        \fill[yellow!50, opacity=0.8] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Bottom face
                        \fill[green!50, opacity=0.8] (E) -- (F) -- (G) -- (H) -- cycle; % Top face
                        \fill[blue!50, opacity=0.8] (A) -- (B) -- (F) -- (E) -- cycle; % Front face
                        \fill[orange!50, opacity=0.8] (B) -- (C) -- (G) -- (F) -- cycle; % Right face
                        \fill[cyan!50, opacity=0.8] (C) -- (D) -- (H) -- (G) -- cycle; % Back face
                        \fill[purple!50, opacity=0.8] (D) -- (A) -- (E) -- (H) -- cycle; % Left face

                        % Draw cube edges
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (E) -- (F) -- (G) -- (H) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (E);
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- (F);
                        \draw[thick] (C) -- (G);
                        \draw[thick] (D) -- (H);

                        % Add dimensions without angle brackets
                        \draw (E) -- (F) node[midway, below] {8 cm};
                        
                         \end{tikzpicture}

                    </latex-image>
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        
                    </image>

                    <p>
                        (a). Sketch the net of the cube
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        (b). Work out the surface area of the cube from its net.
                    </p>
                
        </statement>

        <solution>

            <p>
                (a).   <m>\textbf{The net of the cube is as shown.}</m>
            </p>
                <image width="70%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="cube-net2">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                           % Drawing the vertical part of the net with different colors
                            \fill[yellow!50] (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Missing line
                            \draw (0,4) -- (4,4);
                            
                            % Drawing the horizontal part of the net with different colors
                            \fill[green!50] (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);
                            
                            \fill[blue!50] (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                            \fill[orange!50] (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- cycle;
                            \fill[cyan!50] (-4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (-4,0) -- cycle;
                            \fill[purple!50] (4,-4) -- (8,-4) -- (8,0) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Drawing the edges
                            \draw (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                            \draw (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);
                            
                            % Adding dimension labels
                            \node[left] at (0,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[left] at (0,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[above] at (2,8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (2,-8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (6,0) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (-2,0) {8 cm};
                            
                            % Adding rectangle labels
                            \node at (2,6) {A};
                            \node at (2,2) {B};
                            \node at (2,-2) {C};
                            \node at (2,-6) {D};
                            \node at (-2,-2) {E};
                            \node at (6,-2) {F};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>

             <p>
                (b).   <m>\textbf{The surface area of the cube.}</m>
             </p>   
                   <p>
                    <m>{\color{green} \text{Method 1.}}</m> 
                   </p>
                    <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{The area of one face=} \amp 8 cm \times 8 cm</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 64 cm^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text {There are 6 surfaces.Therefore the surface area of the cube is;} \amp </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp  6 \times 64 cm^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 384 cm^2</mrow>
                    </md> 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       <m>{\color{green} \text{Method 2.}}</m> 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\text {Area of a square=} \amp length \times width</mrow>
                            <mrow>\text {Area of square A}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow>\text {Area of square B}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow>\text {Area of square C}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow>\text {Area of square D}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow>\text {Area of square E}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow>\text {Area of square F}= \amp8cm \times 8 cm </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp64 cm^2 </mrow>
                            <mrow>\text{ surface area}=\amp64 cm^2 +64 cm^2 +64 cm^2 +64 cm^2 +64 cm^2 +64 cm^2  </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp  384 cm^2</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
               
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>